The more you get to know a language, the more you come to expect certain letter combinations and recognize other combinations as strange.  This is something we crossword solvers note all the time.  We may be tempted to put a word into the grid, but if it leads to the cross having the letters "xrz" in succession, we will almost certainly pause before entering our guess.  That letter combination doesn't look like it belongs in an English word.

In dealing with foreign languages, our familiarity with what sounds and letters and combinations is less certain, but we still have  some experience and expectations.  ERHU went against my expectations with respect to Chinese, but, given how little I know that language, this was not terribly surprising. Including this sentiment in my post was a call to others, like @Tahoma, to increase my understanding.

